This is one of the most Beauty full Songs originate from Koch Rajbongshi community folk songs.
This language written from from year of 1555 when Koch king Naranarayan (Mallodhwaj) sent the letter to Ahom king, He used this Koch Rajbongshi language and its convert to goalpariya language in 1968(after undivided goalpara district include in Assam) .This Rajbongshi language   in North Bengal(WB) is known as kamatapuri(Rajbongshi) language.
The same Koch Rajbongshi community folks songs is known as Goalpariya (Rajbonsghi/Kamatapuri)  in Assam , Bhawoiya and sotka in Bengal, Desi/bhaowaiya in Bangladesh and Rajbongshi in Nepal.

So this Koch Rajbongshi community folks songs...👍👍

লিরিকঃ দিনে দিনে খসিয়া পড়িবে

দিনে দিনে খসিয়া পড়িবে
রঙ্গিলা দালানের মাটি গো সাঁইজি কোন রঙে।।

বাঁধিছেন ঘর মিছা, মিছা দন্ধ মাঝে গোসাঁইজি ...
কোন রঙে।।

বাল্য না কাল গেলো হাসিতে খেলিতে
যৈবন কাল গেলো রঙ্।।
আর বৃদ্ধ না কাল গেলো ভাবিতে চিন্তিতে
গুরু ভজিবো কোন কালে, গোঁসাইজী ... কোন রঙে।
ও দিনে দিনে খসিয়া পড়িবে
রঙ্গিলা দালানের মাটি গোঁসাইজী ... কোন রঙে।

হাড়েরও ঘরখানি, চামেরও ছাউনি
বন্ধে বন্ধে তার জোড়া
আর তাহারই তলে ময়ুর আর ময়ুরী
শূন্যে উড়ায় তারা গোসাঁইজি ... কোন রঙে
(আরেক বইয়ে লেখা)

হাড়েরও ঘরখানি, চামেরও ছাউনি
বন্ধে বন্ধে জোড়া
সেই ঝড়েরও প্রহরী ময়ুর আর ময়ুরী
কবে দেয় যে গো উড়া গোসাঁইজি ... কোন রঙ

snippet.textDisplay:
For the Assamese-Bengali debate:
It's neither Assamese nor Bengali. It is Goalpariya which is dialectal to Koch Rajbongsi, Kamtapuri, Rangpuri and Rajbansi. (Some count Surjapuri as well).

Goalparia is a Bengali-Assamese language just like Assamese, Bengali, Chittagonian, Nokhailla, Sylheti, Bishnupriya Manipuri, Chakma, Mymensinghiya, Tanchanggya etc. 

It is most closely related to its neighbours: Rajshahia, Dinajpuria, Western Assamese (Borpeita, Kamruipa, Nolbaira, Darrangia), Mymensinghiya etc. 

Goalparia is considered as a descendant of Kamarupi Prakrit, along with Assamese. 

It is interesting that to many people Goalpariya sound like both Bengali and Assamese. 

This is because the Western dialect of Goalpariya, Rangpuri, Kamtapuri etc don't have /s/ > /x, h/ shifting. It has /tʃ/ and I think dental and retroflexes as well. 
These sounds disappeared in Assamese from their original places. But many of these sounds are still present in Bengali. That's the reason. 

Interestingly Old Assamese is very similar to Goalpariya. 
You can get Old Assamese (13-17th century) texts here:
https://as.m.wikisource.org/wiki/%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%AA%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A3%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A1_%E0%A7%B0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A6%A3

It's Saptakanda Ramayana written in 14th century mainly, by Madhava Kandali (2 of the 7 cantos were written in 15-16th century by Sankardeva and Madhav deva) in Central Assam. 

It's quite similar to both Goalpariya and Bengali. 

And just like Assamese, Bengali too have shiftings. 

Like khoshia (dialectal: khoshi) would be khoshe in Bengali and khohi in Assamese. And khosia in Old Assamese and Old Bengali.
In Eastern Goalpariya it's khohi.
